Comment:
Notes by Travis Colon.

This is my first annotated game. I assume that my audience has some intermediate knowledge of the opening, so I do not go into theory, mostly strategies and concrete variations. This is just a practice run against a weaker opponent. My future games will be played and annotated much better.

We see a strange variation similar to a King's Indian. However, he declines c4, the most popular continuation. I should have exploited this with an immediate ..d5. I did not, and he should have went with an immediate e4. He does not, however, and the game soon shifts in black's favor.

White holds the d pawn, but his e pawn is blocked and his king side development is hindered substantially. On the other hand, my king is sheltered and my development is better. I use this opportunity to try a breakthrough in the center...
...And he closes.
...And he closes.

Closing the center is a common response to ...e5, when there is a white pawn on e4 to support it. Now I re-open the game in a manner beneficial for me, and attempt to exploit the absence of a pawn on e4. I can undermine d5 with c6 and move my center pawns forward with great affect.
He leaves his knight en prise, making e4 dangerous. I did not notice such threat until a few moves later, unfortunately. My observational abilities are apparently quite weak.

I go along with my plan to undermine d5.

bxc6 is stronger than nxc6. If he pushes g5 for any reason then f5 is still available for my knight. The a6-f1 diagonal is open and so is the b-file, and now a pawn on d5 is very strong. I may even decide to place a knight on d5 in the future.

The idea behind this is to open up my bishop's diagonal and win the exchange by tactical means. Little did I know that winning the exchange would cost me the exchange, as I will explain later. ...d5 was probably the superior choice, but I was afraid that I would not be able to hold the e pawn,

14.nxe4 wins the exchange, however, my dark square weaknesses would force me to give the exchange back. Even so, I think I would emerge with an advantage.

14.nxe4 nxe4 15. fxe4 bxa1 16.qxa1, and I don't see how I can stop 17.bh6, threatening mate. 16...f6 loses the pawn, and the only way to block the queen on the diagonal is to wait for bh6 so that I may push my pawn to f6, allowing white to capture my rook. I still appear to be OK, but I think capturing with the pawn as white did in the game was a lot better for me. Now the knight in being attacked by the bishop. The next move is forced.

I for one would rather keep it.
Now my threat is qh4  Developing his knight to f3 is probably best.

A Fatal mistake,as white loses the rook. Nf3 would have developed a piece and prevented the threat. Had he done so, I would have made my pawn thrust f5, strengthening my position even further, and eventually allowing me to open up the e or d file. With a centered king and queen, this would be equally lethal, although winning would have required a lot more work from me. His game is now completely hopeless.
